Wirecard and Greensill: Emerging Risk Blindness in the 2020s
Introduction: The Architecture of Emerging Risk Blindness
The early 2020s marked a profound and disruptive watershed era in global financial risk management. This period was defined by the spectacular, multi-billion-dollar collapses of two ostensibly revolutionary financial technology (fintech) entities: the German payments processor Wirecard AG in 2020, and the British supply chain finance firm Greensill Capital in 2021. These failures did not merely represent instances of isolated corporate malfeasance or idiosyncratic market blowouts; rather, they exposed a systemic and deeply embedded vulnerability across the global financial architecture. This phenomenon, which can be defined as "emerging risk blindness," characterizes the fundamental inability of traditional financial institutions, regulatory bodies, and statutory auditors to identify, comprehend, and mitigate the novel risks introduced by hyper-growth, technologically complex, and structurally opaque non-bank financial intermediation (NBFI) models.1
As financial technology rapidly evolved over the preceding decade, the complexity of fintech supply chains, the velocity of their transaction volumes, and the deliberate obfuscation of their balance sheets vastly outpaced the cyclical, backward-looking risk identification processes of established institutions.1 Traditional risk frameworks—heavily reliant on historical data, static Value-at-Risk (VaR) models, and rigid regulatory perimeters—proved structurally incapable of capturing the transitive counterparty risks, operational vulnerabilities, and fraudulent machinations embedded within these new business models.5 Established banks treated fintech partners as standard vendors or traditional corporate borrowers, completely failing to underwrite them as systemic risk nodes capable of transmitting severe financial shocks.1
This comprehensive research report provides an exhaustive forensic analysis of the Wirecard and Greensill failures, examining the mechanics of their operations, the resulting contagion across traditional banking counterparties, and the profound failures of governance and regulatory oversight. Furthermore, the analysis explores the underlying taxonomy of emerging risk blindness and details how advanced foresight methodologies—such as the Delphi method, horizon scanning, and scenario analysis—alongside comprehensive regulatory overhauls like the EU Digital Operational Resilience Act (DORA), are being deployed by the financial sector to cure the systemic blindness that allowed these crises to manifest.8
Part I: The Wirecard Fraud (1999–2020)
Wirecard AG, once heralded as the crown jewel of European fintech and an elite member of the prestigious DAX 30 index, collapsed in June 2020 after acknowledging a €1.9 billion void in its balance sheet.11 The company's demise represents one of the most severe auditing and regulatory failures in modern financial history, orchestrated by a highly centralized, autocratic management team and enabled by a credulous financial establishment that chose to believe the narrative of a continuous technological miracle rather than heed mounting red flags.13
1.1 The Mechanics of the Fraud and Corporate Structure
Founded in Munich in 1999, Wirecard initially specialized in processing payments for high-risk online sectors, including gambling and pornography.11 In 2002, Markus Braun, a former KPMG consultant, took over as Chief Executive Officer, steering the company toward rapid expansion. In 2005, Wirecard entered the Frankfurt stock market by taking over the listing of a defunct call center, a reverse-merger maneuver that allowed it to avoid the intense scrutiny of a traditional Initial Public Offering (IPO).11
In 2006, the firm acquired XCOM, which provided it with a banking license and led to the creation of Wirecard Bank.11 This hybrid structure—merging an unregulated technology holding company with a regulated bank—was instrumental to the overarching fraud. It rendered Wirecard's financial statements exceptionally difficult to compare against traditional payment processing peers and allowed management to rely heavily on "adjusted" versions of financial statements to present an illusion of relentless profitability.11
The core mechanism of the deception was the Third Party Acquiring (TPA) business. Wirecard claimed that in jurisdictions where it lacked its own acquiring licenses—primarily across Asia and the Middle East—it relied on third-party partners such as Al Alam in Dubai, PayEasy in the Philippines, and Senjo in Singapore.11 Wirecard accounted for these TPA revenues on a gross basis, classifying itself as the "principal" under IFRS accounting standards, which artificially inflated its top-line revenue and apparent market dominance.16 When later scrutinized by auditors, Wirecard utilized the "aggregator merchant" defense, claiming it only dealt with payment facilitators and had no direct contractual relationships with the underlying sub-merchants, thus effectively obfuscating the non-existence of actual transaction volumes.16
1.2 The Financial Times Investigation and Corporate Retaliation
The unravelling of Wirecard was not driven by regulators or auditors, but by a relentless, multi-year investigation by the Financial Times (FT), spearheaded by investigative journalist Dan McCrum. The FT's "House of Wirecard" series began on the FT Alphaville blog in 2015, raising initial questions about a €250 million discrepancy in the group's accounts.11
The reporting timeline accelerated sharply in early 2018 when an internal whistleblower in Wirecard's Singapore headquarters, Pav Gill, exposed a "round-tripping" scheme designed to fraudulently backdate contracts and send money to India via third parties to artificially inflate profits.11 In January 2019, the FT published its first major exposé based on these internal documents.11 In April 2019, FT journalists physically visited the supposed headquarters of Wirecard's Philippine partners, discovering a retired seaman's residential home and a bus company office instead of an international payments hub.11 By October 2019, the FT published documents proving that profits in Dubai and Dublin were fraudulently inflated and that listed customers did not exist.11
Wirecard's response to the FT was characterized by extreme hostility and sophisticated corporate espionage, enabled by massive financial resources. To protect his sources and data, McCrum was forced to adopt extreme operational security measures, including using untraceable prepaid burner phones, air-gapped Chromebook laptops, and encrypted Signal communications.18 The company deployed the London law firm Schillings to issue aggressive legal threats, hired public relations firm FTI Consulting to manage the narrative, and utilized private investigators to conduct surveillance on journalists and short-sellers.11 In a severe escalation, FT journalists and researchers were targeted with sophisticated "spearphishing" cyber-attacks, and Wirecard allegedly colluded with a former Libyan intelligence chief, Rami El Obeidi, in a sting operation to falsely accuse the FT of market manipulation and collusion with short-sellers.11
1.3 Regulatory Failure: BaFin's Blind Spot and the Parliamentary Inquiry
The German Federal Financial Supervisory Authority (BaFin) exhibited a profound manifestation of emerging risk blindness, acting to protect the domestic fintech champion rather than investigating the substantive, documented allegations of fraud.19
BaFin’s oversight was hampered by a fragmented and overly complex regulatory landscape. Germany operated a two-tier enforcement system involving the Financial Reporting Enforcement Panel (FREP) and BaFin, leading to a lack of clear leadership, duplicated competencies, and systemic inertia.19 Furthermore, regional Bavarian authorities erroneously classified Wirecard as a non-financial technology company, exempting the parent holding company from stringent anti-money laundering (AML) and banking supervision, demonstrating how new business models easily fall through the cracks of traditional regulatory perimeters.19
Rather than scrutinizing Wirecard's balance sheet, BaFin exhibited severe regulatory capture and a bias toward protecting national economic interests. In 2016, the regulator chose to investigate anonymous short-sellers (operating under the pseudonym Zatarra) for market manipulation after they alleged money laundering at Wirecard.11 In an unprecedented market intervention in February 2019, following the FT's Singapore exposé, BaFin instituted a two-month ban on the short selling of Wirecard stock, explicitly citing a threat to market confidence.11 Subsequently, BaFin filed criminal complaints against the FT journalists, further enabling the fraud to persist.11
The subsequent German Parliamentary inquiry highlighted these catastrophic structural weaknesses. The inquiry revealed that BaFin was hierarchical and heavily influenced by the Ministry of Finance, suffering from a lack of independence and an over-reliance on a flawed, under-resourced auditor oversight body (APAS).19 The parliamentary findings underscored that supervisors were paralyzed by the complexity of Wirecard's international operations and defaulted to trusting the audited financial statements rather than engaging in proactive, skeptical investigation.19
1.4 The Audit Failure: EY and KPMG
The statutory audit of Wirecard by Ernst & Young (EY) represents a catastrophic failure of professional skepticism and a textbook example of the "audit expectation gap".19 EY served as Wirecard's auditor for over a decade, consistently issuing unqualified "clean" audit opinions until the very end.19 The audit failure stemmed from EY's willingness to accept management representations without corroborating evidence, a reliance on electronic copies rather than original documents, and a failure to independently verify the existence of the offshore escrow accounts that purportedly held the TPA cash.19
Under mounting pressure from investors following the FT's October 2019 reports, Wirecard commissioned KPMG to conduct an independent special audit.11 The KPMG report, published on April 27, 2020, was damning and ultimately triggered the collapse. KPMG explicitly stated that it could not verify the "lion's share" of profits from the TPA business between 2016 and 2018.11


