	1.5 Systemic Exposure, Key Actors, and Total Loss
The fraud was orchestrated from the top by CEO Markus Braun and Chief Operating Officer Jan Marsalek. Academic and professional analyses subsequently characterized their leadership as exhibiting deep-seated narcissism, psychopathy, and Machiavellian traits that defined the company's aggressive, secretive internal culture and its "tone from the top".11 Following the KPMG report, on June 16, 2020, Philippine banks officially informed EY that documents confirming €1.9 billion in balances were entirely "spurious".11 Wirecard filed for insolvency on June 25, 2020, admitting the cash likely did not exist.11 Braun was arrested, while Marsalek utilized his connections with various intelligence agencies to flee the jurisdiction, becoming an international fugitive.11
The collapse transmitted severe counterparty risk across the traditional banking sector, which had fundamentally failed to underwrite the fintech's opaque structure. A syndicate of 15 major financial institutions had provided a €1.75 billion revolving credit facility to Wirecard, which was 90% drawn at the time of insolvency.24 The banks' risk identification processes failed because they relied on the superficial comfort of EY's clean audit opinions, Wirecard's DAX 30 status, and the assumption that a regulated entity (Wirecard Bank) implied the soundness of the entire corporate group.12


