Part II: The Collapse of Greensill Capital (2021)
Less than a year after Wirecard’s implosion, the global financial system was rocked by the collapse of Greensill Capital in March 2021. Founded by charismatic Australian financier Lex Greensill, the firm weaponized the accounting treatment of supply chain finance (SCF), transforming a traditionally low-risk, self-liquidating trade finance instrument into speculative, unsecured corporate debt.27 The failure exposed how fintechs can exploit regulatory blind spots and co-opt established banks to distribute toxic risk to unsuspecting investors.
2.1 The Business Model: Reverse Factoring and "Prospective Receivables"
Standard supply chain finance, or reverse factoring, is a well-established mechanism where a financial intermediary pays a buyer's supplier early at a slight discount, and later collects the full invoice amount from the highly-rated corporate buyer at maturity.27 This model relies on the arbitrage of credit ratings between large buyers and smaller suppliers, providing vital liquidity to the supply chain.
Greensill Capital fundamentally distorted this model to fuel its exponential growth. The firm engaged heavily in the financing of "prospective receivables"—extending capital to companies based on anticipated, future business rather than finalized, legally binding invoices for goods already delivered.27 As identified by the UK Treasury Committee, this practice completely severed the link to actual trade, rendering the financing "more akin to straightforward unsecured lending".27
Furthermore, the widespread use of SCF allowed buying firms to obscure their true level of indebtedness. Because SCF facilities are often classified as trade payables rather than financial debt on corporate balance sheets, credit rating agencies, auditors, and investors were blinded to the true leverage of the underlying corporates.27 Greensill exploited this accounting gray area to originate billions in loans that traditional banks would have rejected.
2.2 Credit Suisse and the $10 Billion Supply Chain Finance Funds
Greensill's rapid expansion was entirely dependent on its ability to securitize these high-risk loans and offload them to institutional investors. Its primary conduit was Credit Suisse Asset Management (CSAM), which established four Supply Chain Finance Funds that ultimately held $10 billion in assets.31 Credit Suisse aggressively marketed these funds to its ultra-high-net-worth wealth management clients as low-risk, highly liquid alternatives to money market funds, relying on the purported safety of the underlying credit insurance rather than conducting independent credit analysis on the underlying borrowers.33
The Credit Suisse internal investigations—most notably the 165-page report conducted by the law firm Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton & Garrison—and subsequent enforcement findings by the Swiss financial regulator FINMA, revealed a catastrophic breakdown in the bank's governance and risk architecture.31 The investigations identified "serious deficiencies in risk management," noting a permissive commercial relationship with clients and a pervasive culture of lax risk mitigation.36
Credit Suisse operated with a weak "tone from the top," prioritizing short-term revenue generation and asset gathering in its Asset Management and Prime Services divisions over prudent counterparty risk assessment.36 Crucially, Credit Suisse essentially outsourced its First Line of Defense to Greensill. The bank's asset management company had "little knowledge and control over the specific claims," leaving Greensill to originate the loans, securitize the debt into notes, and procure the underlying insurance without rigorous independent verification by the bank's risk officers.33 The Paul Weiss report concluded that the bank was "focused on maximizing short-term profits and failed to rein in and, indeed, enabled... voracious risk-taking".37 This systemic failure was concurrent with the bank's massive losses to Archegos Capital Management, highlighting a deeply embedded cultural blindness to interconnected risk that eventually forced the resignation of Chairman António Horta-Osório, who had been brought in to clean up the exact same risk management failures.31
2.3 The Single Point of Failure: Trade Credit Insurance
The entire $10 billion architecture of the Credit Suisse funds rested on a single, highly fragile pillar: trade credit insurance provided primarily by Tokio Marine, facilitated through an underwriter named Greg Brereton based in Sydney.27 The insurance policies were intended to guarantee the repayment of the notes if the underlying corporate borrowers defaulted. This insurance wrapper was the mechanism that allowed Credit Suisse to categorize the notes as investment-grade equivalents and market them as low-risk.33
When Tokio Marine conducted internal reviews and discovered the sheer extent of the concentration risk and the highly unconventional nature of the "prospective receivables," it terminated Brereton and explicitly refused to renew the insurance coverage.32 The expiration of this coverage in early March 2021 stripped the notes of their protective wrapper, triggering an immediate liquidity crisis.28 Without valid insurance, Credit Suisse was forced to freeze and liquidate the $10 billion funds, instantly severing Greensill's funding pipeline and bankrupting the firm.31 The reliance on a single underwriter for billions of dollars of systemic exposure exemplifies a profound failure in identifying third-party concentration risk. Subsequent litigation, including a $143 million lawsuit by investor White Oak against insurance broker Marsh for allegedly failing to disclose these insurance problems from as early as July 2020, highlights the systemic opacity and negligence of the arrangement.32
2.4 Concentration Risk and Political Lobbying
Greensill's risk profile was further distorted by an extreme, almost fatalistic concentration of exposure to the GFG Alliance, a loose, opaque network of steel, mining, and industrial companies controlled by magnate Sanjeev Gupta.27 Greensill maintained a "symbiotic relationship" with GFG, continually funneling capital to the alliance despite internal limits and growing market skepticism.27 The UK Treasury Committee noted that despite warnings from the Bank of England regarding GFG-related banks as early as December 2019, information silos prevented the British Business Bank from intervening before government guarantees under the Coronavirus Large Business Interruption Loan Scheme (CLBILS) were extended to Greensill.27
To survive as funding tightened, Lex Greensill aggressively sought access to the UK government's Covid Corporate Financing Facility (CCFF).27 To facilitate this, he employed former UK Prime Minister David Cameron, who held a "very significant personal economic interest" in the firm via stock options, to directly lobby the government.27 Cameron engaged in prolific informal lobbying—sending text messages and emails to Chancellor Rishi Sunak and other senior Treasury officials—a tactic the Treasury Committee later condemned as demonstrating a "significant lack of judgement".27 During these efforts, Greensill was falsely positioned to the government as a technology-driven "fintech" firm dedicated to helping Small and Medium Enterprises (SMEs), a label the Treasury Committee later described as a deceptive "sales pitch" designed to hide a fundamental financial solvency problem.27
2.5 Total Losses and Contagion
The collapse of Greensill Capital caused an immediate cascade of financial distress. The firm owed $3.44 billion to diverse creditors at the time of its insolvency.32 For Credit Suisse, the fallout was protracted, severe, and ultimately existential.
Of the $10 billion trapped in the frozen supply chain finance funds, the bank managed to return approximately $6.7 to $7 billion to investors within the first two years through the liquidation of standard, high-quality receivables.35 However, recovering the remaining $2.7 billion became mired in tortuous debt renegotiations, complex cross-border litigation, and fiercely disputed insurance claims.35 Credit Suisse was forced to inform the 1,200 trapped investors that full recovery could take over five years, if it occurred at all.35 Despite investor fury, the bank refused to underwrite the clients' losses, fearing it would trigger massive regulatory capital requirements.35 The immense reputational damage caused by the Greensill and Archegos twin failures catalyzed a fatal loss of market confidence, ultimately contributing directly to Credit Suisse's collapse and forced emergency acquisition by UBS in 2023.33


