	Part III: The "Emerging Risk Blindness" Pattern
The concurrent and spectacular failures of Wirecard and Greensill highlight a systemic paradigm within the financial sector termed "emerging risk blindness." This blindness is not merely a failure of individual analysts or isolated compliance officers; it represents a profound epistemological gap between the foundational design of traditional banking risk frameworks and the reality of modern financial technology.1
3.1 Velocity of Growth vs. Risk Cycle Times
Traditional risk identification in banking relies heavily on historical data sets, static regulatory reporting, and periodic (often quarterly or annual) committee reviews.4 Risk models are inherently backward-looking, designed to predict future defaults based on past behavior. Fintechs, conversely, operate on principles of hyper-scalability, exponential growth, and highly agile pivots in business strategy.1
By the time a traditional bank's risk committee categorizes a new exposure type—such as a complex API-driven aggregator model (Wirecard) or a dynamically priced SCF instrument based on prospective receivables (Greensill)—the fintech has already mutated its risk profile or scaled the exposure beyond safe parameters.1 The lag between the velocity of technological adoption and the cycle time of institutional risk audits creates a persistent blind spot where multi-billion-dollar exposures accumulate entirely undetected by legacy frameworks. As noted by the IIF and EY in their Global Bank Risk Management Surveys, 57% of financial institutions expressed deep concern over their ability to keep pace with emerging technology developments and the associated cybersecurity and operational risks.1
3.2 Regulatory Perimeter Evasion and Product Gaps
Both Wirecard and Greensill successfully exploited the gaps between established regulatory perimeters. Financial regulation is inherently categorical; an entity is strictly regulated as a bank, an insurer, or an asset manager. Fintechs explicitly design hybrid models that fall outside these rigid definitions to minimize capital requirements and supervisory oversight.4
Wirecard separated its regulated banking arm (Wirecard Bank) from its unregulated parent holding company, effectively neutralizing holistic supervision by BaFin, which claimed it only had jurisdiction over the banking subsidiary.11 Greensill utilized the UK's "Appointed Representatives" (AR) regime—originally designed in 1986 to allow self-employed salespeople to sell simple insurance products—to operate under the regulatory umbrella of a principal firm (Mirabella). This allowed Greensill to originate billions in complex corporate debt without requiring direct, rigorous authorization and scrutiny by the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA).27
Furthermore, new product types consistently fall between existing risk categories. By classifying its lending as "supply chain finance," Greensill avoided the stringent underwriting standards associated with unsecured corporate debt, exploiting the fact that SCF was not captured within the traditional regulatory perimeter for financial services.27 This dynamic is equally visible in other modern fintech products. Buy Now, Pay Later (BNPL) platforms often structure their products to avoid classification as consumer credit, bypassing affordability checks, while Crypto Custody services blur the lines between asset holding and liability creation, creating profound legal and capital uncertainties.
3.3 The Complexity of Third-Party and Counterparty Risk
The digitalization of financial services has transformed bilateral counterparty relationships into complex, multi-tiered, interdependent supply chains. The Institute of International Finance (IIF) and McKinsey noted in their global surveys that Third-Party Risk Management (TPRM) is the single greatest capability weakness in the financial sector, cited by 65% of Chief Risk Officers.1
Banks generally treat fintech partners as standard operational vendors, applying traditional procurement due diligence rather than evaluating them as systemic risk nodes capable of transmitting severe financial shocks.1 In the case of Wirecard, the syndicates lending €1.75 billion failed to demand direct verification of the underlying TPA sub-merchants, relying instead on the fintech's DAX 30 status and superficial audited accounts.24 In the case of Greensill, Credit Suisse failed to look through the fintech originator to evaluate the ultimate underlying risk—the financial health of the GFG Alliance and the fragility of the single Tokio Marine insurance wrap.27 This blindness to transitive counterparty risk in complex supply chains is the defining characteristic of the 2020s fintech crises. Organizations operate "flying blind," lacking the metrics and reporting necessary to prove the resilience of their vendors in times of extreme stress.1
Part IV: Horizon Scanning and the Delphi Method
Recognizing the structural failure of traditional risk models to capture these non-financial, highly interconnected threats, financial institutions and macro-prudential regulators are increasingly turning to advanced foresight methodologies to cure emerging risk blindness. Techniques such as the Delphi method, scenario analysis, and horizon scanning shift risk management from a reactive, backward-looking compliance exercise to a proactive, dynamic discipline.6
4.1 Advanced Foresight Methodologies
The Delphi Method: Originating from systematic forecasting in the defense sector, the Delphi method is an iterative, structured process of expert elicitation designed to build consensus on highly uncertain topics where historical data is entirely absent—such as the emergence of novel fintech business models or catastrophic cyber-risks.8 Experts (internal risk managers, external technologists, legal counsel) are subjected to multiple rounds of anonymous questionnaires. After each round, the aggregated results, along with the justifications provided by the experts, are fed back to the panel, allowing individuals to adjust their forecasts based on peer reasoning.50
This methodology is critical for breaking down institutional silos and groupthink. The anonymity eliminates the "loudest voice in the room" bias and hierarchical deference, enabling risk functions to surface contrarian views on emerging threats—such as the systemic reliance on a single insurance provider or the opacity of offshore accounting practices—before they materialize into terminal losses.50
Scenario Analysis and Horizon Scanning: While traditional Value-at-Risk (VaR) isolates historical volatility on a single asset class, scenario analysis projects the compounding consequences of interconnected risks.6 It forces institutions to ask systemic questions: "What happens if a major third-party technology provider fails simultaneously with a market liquidity shock?".6 Horizon scanning complements this by systematically monitoring weak signals in the data ecosystem—such as a sudden surge in the use of "prospective receivables" in corporate filings, or unusually rapid growth in a specific NBFI sector—to detect overarching changes in market behavior before they appear in default statistics.9
4.2 Institutional Warnings on Fintech and NBFI Risks
Despite the catastrophic failures at the institutional level (e.g., Credit Suisse, Commerzbank), macroeconomic monitoring bodies had successfully utilized horizon scanning and expert consensus to warn of the exact risks that brought down Wirecard and Greensill. The failure was not in the identification of the macro-trend, but in the translation of that trend into micro-prudential action.
The World Economic Forum (WEF): The WEF's Global Risks Report—itself heavily reliant on expert perception surveys akin to Delphi methodologies—consistently highlighted the dangers of technological dependence and cyber vulnerabilities long before the 2020s crises. Since 2017 and 2018, the reports warned of the accelerating pace of technological change leading to "risk blindness" and explicitly identified cyber-attacks, data fraud, and the breakdown of critical information infrastructure as top global risks by both likelihood and impact.55
Bank of England Financial Stability Reports (FSR): The Bank of England demonstrated acute foresight regarding the vulnerabilities of non-bank financial intermediation. In its July 2019 FSR, the Financial Policy Committee (FPC) warned explicitly about the systemic risk posed by the liquidity mismatch in open-ended investment funds.58 The FPC noted that offering daily redemptions while investing in illiquid corporate assets creates a dangerous "first-mover advantage," incentivizing a rapid run on the fund during periods of stress, which forces fire sales and amplifies market panic.58 This was the exact structural flaw that triggered the freezing of Credit Suisse’s $10 billion Greensill funds when the underlying supply chain notes suddenly became unmarketable due to the loss of insurance.31 The FSRs also continually flagged leveraged lending and the reliance on complex chains of receivables as areas of intense vulnerability.30
IIF and EY Global Risk Surveys: The joint annual surveys of Chief Risk Officers (CROs) by the IIF and EY consistently demonstrated that while cyber security and operational resilience were identified as top-tier threats, institutions lacked the agility and critical thinking skills to manage them effectively.3 The surveys highlighted that the transition to digital strategies and the adoption of fintech partnerships were moving faster than banks could deploy risk mitigation tactics, resulting in a dangerous reliance on outdated legacy controls.5 By 2023, 61% of survey respondents explicitly cited talent gaps as a key risk to establishing oversight capabilities for emerging technology.59


